{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2016}} {{Infobox person | image = Joel McHale 2014 Comic Con (cropped).jpg | caption = McHale at the 2014 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]] | birth_name = Joel Edward McHale | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1971|11|20}} | birth_place = [[Rome]], Italy | occupation = {{hlist|Comedian|actor|writer|producer|television host}} | residence = [[Hollywood Hills]], [[California]], U.S. | alma_mater = [[University of Washington]] | spouse = {{Marriage|Sarah Williams|1996}} | children = 2 | years_active = 1993â€“present | notable_works = {{Plainlist| * ''[[The Soup]]'' * ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'' * ''[[The Joel McHale Show with Joel McHale]]'' }} | nationality = American | module = {{Infobox comedian|embed=yes | medium = {{hlist|Film|television|[[stand-up comedy|stand-up]]}} | genre = {{hlist|[[Political satire]]|[[observational comedy]]}} | subject = {{hlist|[[Celebrities]]|[[popular culture|pop culture]]|[[American culture]]}} | website = {{URL|http://www.joelmchale.com}} }} }} '''Joel Edward McHale''' (born November 20, 1971)<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Smith|first=Grady|url=http://www.ew.com/article/2011/11/18/monitor-nov-25-2011|title=Monitor: Nov. 25, 2011|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|issue=1182|page=30|date=November 25, 2011|accessdate=April 4, 2015}}</ref> is an American comedian, actor, writer, television producer, and television host. He is known for hosting ''[[The Soup]]'' and portraying [[Jeff Winger]] on the [[NBC]]/[[Yahoo!]] sitcom ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]''. He has appeared in the films ''[[Spy Kids: All the Time in the World]]'' (2011) and ''[[Ted (film)|Ted]]'' (2012). He also starred in the short-lived [[CBS]] sitcom ''[[The Great Indoors (TV series)|The Great Indoors]]''.
==Early life== McHale was born in [[Rome]], [[Italy]], where his father, Jack McHale, worked as [[Dean of Students]] at [[Loyola University Chicago|Loyola University]] Rome Center. His mother, Laurie, is from [[Vancouver, British Columbia|Vancouver]], [[Canada]]; and his father is from [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]].<ref>[http://www.pnwlocalnews.com/east_king/mir/lifestyle/35031314.html Mercer Island dons its autumn cloak] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110131192559/http://www.pnwlocalnews.com/east_king/mir/lifestyle/35031314.html |date=January 31, 2011 }}, pnwlocalnews.com; accessed February 25, 2014</ref> Of [[Irish people|Irish]] and [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] descent,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1203/15/pmt.01.html|title=PIERS MORGAN TONIGHT, One-on-one with Joel McHale; The Great Anjelica Huston|date=March 15, 2012|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref> he was raised [[Catholic Church|Catholic]]. He grew up on [[Mercer Island, Washington]], and briefly in [[Haddonfield, New Jersey]], near [[Philadelphia]], before returning to his native Washington state.<ref>{{cite web |last=Strawberry |first=Saroyan |url=http://www.details.com/story/soup-host-joel-mchale-is-the-funniest-man-on-tv |title=Joel McHale |work=[[Details (magazine)|Details]] |date=June 2008 |accessdate=December 19, 2015}}</ref> He attended [[Mercer Island High School]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Brodeur |first=Nicole |url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20040822&slug=joelmchale22 |title=From Mercer Island, jumping into "The Soup" |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |date=August 22, 2004 |accessdate=December 19, 2015}}</ref>
McHale received a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[History]] from the [[University of Washington]] (1995) and briefly belonged to [[Theta Chi]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Curran|first=Dan|title=An interview with the king of snark Joel McHale|url=http://onmilwaukee.com/ent/articles/joelmchale.html|accessdate=March 30, 2012|newspaper=onmilwaukee.com|date=October 16, 2008}}</ref>
He was recruited to be on the [[Rowing (sport)|rowing]] team but later joined the [[Washington Huskies football|football team]]. Though most of his teammates received athletic [[scholarship]]s, McHale was a [[Walk-on (sports)|walk on]] playing [[tight end]] for two years.<ref>{{cite news|last=Steinberg|first=Dan|title=THECHAT: Joel McHale|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A22047-2005Feb13.html?sub%3Dnew?=AR%20THECHAT|page=D02|accessdate=March 30, 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=February 14, 2005}}</ref> He received a [[Master of Fine Arts]] degree from the Professional Actors Training Program at the [[University of Washington]]. He is a fan of the [[Seattle Seahawks]].<ref>{{cite web|last=McHale|first=Joel|title=The Walk-On: The Community star recalls his two-year football career at the University of Washington|url=http://www.grantland.com/story/_/id/7035000/the-walk-on|work=Grantland|publisher=ESPN Ventures|accessdate=March 30, 2012|date=September 29, 2011}}</ref>
==Career==
===Comedy=== McHale was part of the ''[[Almost Live!]]'' cast, a local [[sketch-comedy]] television show produced by Seattle's [[KING-TV]] (broadcast Channel 5). From 1993 to 1997, he was a member of the [[improv comedy]] group at [[Unexpected Productions]], participating in Theatersports! at the Market Theater located in [[Pike Place Market]] in downtown Seattle.<ref>[http://www.unexpectedproductions.org/about.htm International Improv Festival] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081010084039/http://www.unexpectedproductions.org/about.htm |date=October 10, 2008 }}; accessed February 25, 2014</ref>
===Acting=== After earning his master's degree in acting, McHale moved to Los Angeles and landed small roles in ''[[Diagnosis: Murder]]'', ''[[CSI: Miami]]'', and ''[[Will & Grace]]''. He played a TV reporter in the biopic ''[[Lords of Dogtown]]''. He guest-starred as a cast member on the [[NBC]] improv comedy show ''[[Thank God You're Here (US TV series)|Thank God You're Here]]'' during the pilot episode and had a guest role on an episode of ''[[Pushing Daisies]]''. McHale also appeared in ''[[Spider-Man 2]]'' in a small role as Mr. Jacks, a bank manager.<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0316654/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm] imdb.com ''Spider-Man 2''</ref>
In 2004 McHale began hosting ''[[The Soup]]'', a satirical weekly television show on the "E!" television network. Throughout the show, he takes the audience through the oddities and ridiculous happenings of the week in television. He frequently appears as a co-host on ''[[Loveline]]''. He has also had a long association with [[Circle X Theatre]], where he has done several plays. McHale was a weekly guest on ''[[The Adam Carolla Show (radio)|The Adam Carolla Show]]'' and ''[[Mickey and Amelia]]'', and occasional guest on the ''[[Opie and Anthony Show]]''.<ref>[http://www.foundrymusic.com/opieanthony/displayheadline.cfm/id/12764/div/opieanthony/headline/Monday_Opie_and_Anthony_Links__Joel_McHale__New_O_A_Videos__Good_bye_Syracuse__Traveling_Virus_Tickets_On_Sale_Now__New_Videos_Online.html Joel McHale on Opie and Anthony]; accessed February 25, 2014</ref> He has been a judge on ''[[Iron Chef America]]''. He was involved in the American version of the British TV show ''[[The IT Crowd]]''.<ref>[http://io9.gizmodo.com/the-failed-u-s-remake-of-the-it-crowd-is-fascinating-t-1557311843 The Failed U.S. Remake Of The IT Crowd Is Fascinating To Watch<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.bbcamerica.com/anglophenia/2014/11/richard-ayoade-regrets-u-s-pilot-crowd Richard Ayoade Regrets Doing the U.S. Pilot for â€˜The IT Crowdâ€™ | Anglophenia | BBC America<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> McHale made a guest appearance on the finale of ''[[Last Comic Standing]]'s'' sixth season, when he recapped the show's events in his typical format of jokes made popular on ''[[The Soup]]''. He occasionally appeared on ''[[Countdown with Keith Olbermann]]'' in a humor sequence closing the show.
McHale starred in the sitcom ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2009/05/nbc-unveils-new-programs-for-next-fall-.html|last=Fernandez|first=Maria Elena|title=NBC unveils new programs for fall|date=April 4, 2009|accessdate=May 4, 2009|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> which premiered in winter 2009, and continued to host ''[[The Soup]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/blog/BC_Beat/12945-E_Expects_Joel_McHale_To_Stay_On_Soup_.php|title=E! Expects Joel McHale To Stay On 'Soup'| last=Weprin|first=Alex|date=May 4, 2009|accessdate=May 4, 2009}}</ref> McHale made an appearance on the first episode of the fifth season of ''[[Tosh.0]]''. He played Rex in ''[[Ted (film)|Ted]]'' (2012) and had a short guest stint on the FX show ''[[Sons of Anarchy]]''. He played an NYPD officer in the supernatural horror film ''[[Deliver Us from Evil (2014 film)|Deliver Us from Evil]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.masslive.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2013/08/joel_mchale_talks_community_so.html|title=Joel McHale talks 'Community,' 'Soup' and upcoming movie|work=masslive.com}}</ref> McHale appeared in 3 episodes between the tenth and eleventh seasons of ''[[The X-Files]]'' in 2016 and 2018, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/675587/why-joel-mchale-is-even-more-excited-about-the-x-files-revival-than-you-are|title=Why Joel McHale Is Even More Excited About The X-Files Revival Than You Are|date=July 14, 2015|work=E! Online|accessdate=January 29, 2016}}</ref>
McHale played the lead role in the CBS sitcom ''[[The Great Indoors (TV series)|The Great Indoors]]'', which began airing in the Fall of 2016.<ref>Wagmeister, Elizabeth (February 16, 2016). [https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/joel-mchale-the-great-indoors-cbs-cast-1201705277/ "Joel McHale to Star in CBS Comedy Pilot 'The Great Indoors.'"] ''Variety.com''. Retrieved May 19, 2016.</ref><ref>Rife, Katie (May 18, 2016). [http://www.avclub.com/article/manly-men-and-eccentric-geniuses-dominate-cbss-fal-236955 "Manly Men and Eccentric Geniuses Dominate CBSâ€™s Fall Schedule."] ''AVClub.com''. Retrieved May 19, 2016.</ref>
In 2018, McHale was cast in the recurring role of Chris on the second season of the [[Netflix]] horror-comedy series ''[[Santa Clarita Diet]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2018/02/santa-clarita-diet-joel-mchale-maggie-lawson-gerald-mcraney-zachary-knighton-guest-star-season-2-1202291505/|title=â€˜Santa Clarita Dietâ€™: Joel McHale, Maggie Lawson, Gerald McRaney & Zachary Knighton To Guest Star In Season 2|last=Petski|first=Denise|date=February 16, 2018|work=Deadline|accessdate=April 1, 2018}}</ref>
===Hosting=== McHale was the host at the 2014 [[White House Correspondents' Association]] annual dinner.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-joel-mchale-host-white-house-correspondents-dinner-20140214,0,3433623.story#axzz2tKKOOx2y|title=Joel McHale will host the White House Correspondents' Dinner|accessdate=February 14, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|date=February 14, 2014}}</ref> He hosted the 2011 [[Independent Spirit Awards]] and the [[2015 ESPY Awards]]. In 2016, he appeared as an occasional co-host alongside [[Kelly Ripa]] in the [[American Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] morning show ''[[Live! with Kelly and Michael|Live! with Kelly]]''. McHale hosted the [[43rd People's Choice Awards]] on January 18, 2017 and the [[2017 Webby Awards]] on May 15, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/webby-awards-honor-this-years-internet-vips-1202429111/|title=The 21st Annual Webby Awards Honor This Year's Internet VIPs|publisher=Variety|accessdate=May 16, 2017}}</ref>
In January 2018, it was announced that he would be receiving his own talk show on [[Netflix]] in February. ''[[The Joel McHale Show with Joel McHale]]'' combines celebrity guests, pre-taped sketches and video clips in a half-hour series that focuses on pop culture and news from around the world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tvguide.com/news/netflix-joel-mchale-talk-show/|title=Netflix Nabs Joel McHale for Weekly Talk Show|date=2018-01-19|work=TVGuide.com|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en}}</ref>
==Personal life== McHale married Sarah Williams in 1996. They have two sons.<ref>{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080508174518/http://www.psarts.org/Press2007/ExpressYourselfEOnline.html |date=May 8, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|series=The Soup|network=E!|airdate= January 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/23611984|title='Countdown with Keith Olbermann' for March 12|accessdate=January 15, 2010}}</ref> They live in [[Hollywood Hills, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/features/home/la-hm-brown15-2009aug15,0,1880997.story|title='Flipping Out's' Ryan Brown settles down in Los Feliz|work=latimes}}</ref>
